🔹 PART A: NORMALIZE (FROM THE SAME FILE)
________________________________________
🛠 Step 1: Load the CSV
1.	Open Power BI Desktop
2.	Home → Get Data → Text/CSV
3.	Select Sales_Flat.csv
4.	Click Transform Data
➡️ Power Query Editor opens
➡️ One query: Sales_Flat
________________________________________
🧱 Step 2: Create Dimension Tables (From Same File)
✅ Step 2.1: Create Dim_Customer
1.	Right-click Sales_Flat → Duplicate
2.	Rename to Dim_Customer
3.	Keep only:
o	CustomerName
4.	Home → Remove Rows → Remove Duplicates
5.	Add Column → Index Column → From 1
6.	Rename index to CustomerKey
✔ Customer dimension created
________________________________________

🧮 Step 2: Create Fact_Sales
1.	Right-click Sales_Flat → Duplicate
2.	Rename → Fact_Sales
3.	Keep columns:
o	OrderID
o	OrderDate
o	CustomerName
o	Product
o	Sales
o	Quantity
________________________________________
🔗 Step 4: Replace Text with Keys (Normalization)
🔹 Replace CustomerName
1.	Select Fact_Sales
2.	Home → Merge Queries
3.	Merge with Dim_Customer on CustomerName
4.	Expand → CustomerKey
5.	Remove CustomerName
✔ Data is now NORMALIZED
✔ Still using ONE original CSV
________________________________________
📤 Step 6: Export Final Flat Table
1.	Close & Apply
2.	Add Table visual
3.	Click ⋯ → Export data → CSV
🎯 Aim
To normalize a flat CSV dataset in Microsoft Power BI Desktop by creating dimension and fact tables using Power Query, replacing text fields with keys, and exporting the normalized result.
________________________________________
🧭 Algorithm (12 Points)
1.	Open Microsoft Power BI Desktop.
2.	Click Home → Get Data → Text/CSV and select Sales_Flat.csv.
3.	Click Transform Data to open Power Query Editor.
4.	Right-click Sales_Flat query and choose Duplicate to create a new query.
5.	Rename the duplicated query as Dim_Customer.
6.	Keep only the CustomerName column and remove duplicates.
7.	Add an Index Column (From 1) and rename it as CustomerKey.
8.	Duplicate Sales_Flat again and rename it as Fact_Sales.
9.	In Fact_Sales, keep required columns: OrderID, OrderDate, CustomerName, Product, Sales, Quantity.
10.	Use Merge Queries to join Fact_Sales with Dim_Customer on CustomerName.
11.	Expand and keep CustomerKey, then remove the CustomerName column to complete normalization.
12.	Click Close & Apply, create a table visual, and Export the normalized data to CSV.



